Let $A,$ $B,$ and $C$ denote the centers of the smaller circles, the intermediate circle, and the larger circle, respectively. The line joining the centers of i...</think>
\begin{align*}
AB =& \text{distance between the two center circles} \\
&=1+2 \\
=&3 \\
BC =& \text{radius of the larger circle} \\
&=2+3 \\
&=5
\end{align*}

As we can see from the diagram, if the smaller circles have radii of 2 and 3, the radius of the unknown circle would be 5. We can imagine constructing a right triangle that looks like the one below, with $BC$ and $AH$ as two lines on top of one another and $AH$ extended to the right so it intersects $BC$ to an unknown point, $P$.

[asy]
fill(Circle((-1,0),5),gray(0.7));
fill(Circle((-3,0),3),white);
fill(circle((2,0),2),white);
dot((-3,0));
dot((2,0));
draw(Circle((-1,0),5));
draw((-3,0)--(0,0));
draw((2,0)--(4,0));
label("3",(-1.5,0),N);
label("2",(3,0),N);
draw((-2,0)--(-2,2)--(-1,0));
label("$3$",(0,1));
draw((-2,0)--(5,0),dashed);
label{$5$",(2.5,0));
draw((5,0)--(5,2),dashed);
label{$R$",(5,1));
draw((-1,0)--(0,1)--(-2,2));
label("$P$",(0,1),E);
draw((0,1)--(-2,2));[/asy]

Because $AHBP$ is a right triangle with legs of lengths 3 and 2 and a hypotenuse of length 5, we can use the Pythagorean theorem to determine that it is a $3$-by-$4$-by-$5$ right triangle. You may recognize it as a right triangle related to the well-known properties of the 3-4-5 Pythagorean triple, and that the dimensions of $APB$
$$2.5 = \text{length of }AP.$$
Note: By symmetry, the point P would need to divide the line segment $\overline{BC}$ into two equal halves, so the entire base would equal $5$. The height would be $2.5$. By convention, we will label the radius of the unknown circle as R, and $2.5$ is the length of $AP$. Compute $AB^2+BP^2.$ When follows:

\begin{align*}
AB^2 + BP^2 &= (AP + PB)^2 + BP^2 \\
&= (2.5 + 2.5)^2 + (2.5)^2 \\
&= 5^2 + (2.5)^2 \\
&= 25 + 6.25 \\
&= 31.25
\end{align*}

The only expression of the form $R^2$ that is a multiple of $31.25$ is $\boxed{05Rx}$.

